fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
If \mathop {\textrm {char}}\nolimits (\Bbbk )=0, then we know \Bbbk _{0}=\mathbb {Q}. Let r\in \mathbb {Q} be r=a/b for some a,b\in \mathbb {Z} with b\neq 0. Then we see
\sigma (a/b)=\frac {\sigma (a)}{\sigma (b)}=\frac {a}{b}
and the result follows immediately.

If \mathop {\textrm {char}}\nolimits (\Bbbk )=0, then we know \Bbbk _{0}=\mathbb {Q}. Let r\in \mathbb {Q} be r=a/b for some a,b\in \mathbb {Z} with b\neq 0. Then we see
\sigma (a/b)=\frac {\sigma (a)}{\sigma (b)}=\frac {a}{b}
and the result follows immediately.
